  "opinion": "As a 18-year-old full-time student in Milan with a creative mindset and a deep connection to nature through hobbies like hiking and gardening, I've observed how stereotype threat manifests in STEM fields. Stereotype threat is the psychological tension that arises when individuals fear being judged negatively based on group stereotypes, which can impair performance. For me, this is particularly relevant as someone from a family where one parent has an upper secondary education and the other has no formal education—this duality shapes my understanding of systemic barriers. In STEM classrooms, students from underrepresented groups often experience this tension when they’re reminded of stereotypes about their group’s intellectual capabilities. It’s not just about individual anxiety; it’s about the collective weight of societal expectations. I believe we must address stereotype threat in STEM because it directly hinders innovation and diversity. To do so effectively, we need to create inclusive environments where students feel safe to explore without fear of judgment. This could mean integrating more relatable, real-world examples into lessons, fostering mentorship programs that connect students with role models who share similar backgrounds, and implementing anonymous assessments to reduce bias. As someone who values both structure and creativity, I think balancing rigorous academic standards with empathetic teaching practices is key. By addressing stereotype threat, we don’t just improve test scores—we build a more resilient and diverse STEM community where everyone can thrive. After all, innovation thrives in environments where every voice is heard and valued.",
